; DBPS v1.0 Section 5 — Glob Matching Algorithm (Pseudocode)
;
; This document formally specifies the glob matching algorithm used
; throughout the DimensionalBase Protocol.  All implementations MUST
; produce results identical to this algorithm for every input in the
; conformance test vectors.

; ALGORITHM: dbps_match(pattern, path) -> bool
;
; 1. If pattern == "**", return true
; 2. If pattern == path (exact string equality), return true
; 3. If pattern contains no "*" characters, return pattern == path
; 4. Split pattern by "/" into pat_parts
; 5. Split path by "/" into path_parts
; 6. Call match_parts(pat_parts, 0, path_parts, 0)

; ALGORITHM: match_parts(pat, pi, path, qi) -> bool
;
; While pi < len(pat) AND qi < len(path):
;   token = pat[pi]
;
;   If token == "**":
;     If pi == len(pat) - 1:
;       return true                          ; ** at end matches all remaining
;     For skip = qi to len(path):
;       If match_parts(pat, pi+1, path, skip):
;         return true                        ; ** matches 0..N segments
;     return false
;
;   Else if token == "*":
;     pi += 1, qi += 1                      ; * matches exactly one segment
;
;   Else if token == path[qi]:
;     pi += 1, qi += 1                      ; literal match
;
;   Else:
;     return false                           ; mismatch
;
; ; Consume trailing ** patterns (match zero segments)
; While pi < len(pat) AND pat[pi] == "**":
;   pi += 1
;
; return pi == len(pat) AND qi == len(path)

; NOTES:
; - This algorithm has worst-case O(n*m) where n = len(pattern) and
;   m = len(path), due to ** backtracking.  In practice, patterns are
;   short (< 10 segments) so this is not a concern.
; - The algorithm is deterministic: given the same (pattern, path) pair,
;   every conformant implementation MUST return the same boolean result.
; - The conformance test vectors in spec/test-vectors/glob-matching.json
;   MUST all pass for any conformant implementation.
